kpi_info.use:
When PSI is sent from HLR to VLR, the subscriber is paged over SGs interface, and this paging resources are not deleted until the Initial Address Message (IAM) is received for the subscriber. This procedure is called PSI paging. This counter is updated when VLR sends the SGsAP-PAGING-REQUESTs over SGs interface (from MSS/VLR to MME) because of PSI paging.
Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PSI_PAGING_SGS_SUCCESS
kpi_info.use:
When PSI is sent from HLR to VLR, the subscriber is paged over SGs interface, and this paging resources are not deleted until the Initial Address Message (IAM) is received for the subscriber. This procedure is called PSI paging. This counter is updated when both the PSI paging procedure and the fallback to the CS domain by the UE have been successfully performed.
Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PSI_PAGING_SGS_FB_DIFF_MSS
kpi_info.use:
When PSI is sent from HLR to VLR, the subscriber is paged over SGs interface, and this paging resources are not deleted until the Initial Address Message (IAM) is received for the subscriber. This procedure is called PSI paging. This counter is updated when PSI paging procedure was performed over SGs interface and VLR receives a Cancel Location from HLR or Send Identification from another MSS/VLR, so UE makes a successful Location Update to other MSC during CS fallback.
Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PSI_PAGING_SGS_WO_CSFB_ATT
kpi_info.use: When MAP PSI request is received, the MSS starts paging the subscriber over the SGs interface for SMS to gain CS location information without executing CS fallback. The counter is updated independently from the result of the paging procedure. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PSI_PAGING_SGS_WO_CSFB_SUCC
kpi_info.use: When MAP PSI request is received, the MSS starts paging the subscriber over the SGs interface for SMS to gain CS location information without executing CS fallback. The counter is updated when paging procedure has been performed successfully. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: TYPE_0_SM_ON_SGS_ATT
kpi_info.use: When MAP PSI request is received, the MSS starts paging the subscriber over the SGs interface for SMS to gain CS location information without executing CS fallback. When SGsAP-SERVICE-REQUEST is received from MME as response to paging it contains E-CGI and TAI information and also indication whether the UE is in EMM-IDLE of EMM-CONNECTED mode. If EMM-IDLE is indicated, the E-CGI can be considered as valid, because MME executed paging of the UE before answering. If EMM-CONNECTED is indicated the E-CGI may be invalid, because MME has not executed paging and it responses with the last known E-CGI of the UE. In this case MSS sends Type 0 SM over SGs to the UE, and if the received SGsAP-UPLINK-UNITDATA contains E-CGI, that is taken as valid information. If SGsAP-UPLINK-UNITDATA does not contain E-CGI, then MSS uses the last known E-CGI in further procedures.When the MSS has a valid E-CGI it maps this to a 2G/3G CGI and sends that in MAP PSI response. The counter is updated independently from the result of the type 0 SM delivery on SGs interface. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: TYPE_0_SM_ON_SGS_SUCC
kpi_info.use: When MAP PSI request is received, the MSS starts paging the subscriber over the SGs interface for SMS to gain CS location information without executing CS fallback. When SGsAP-SERVICE-REQUEST is received from MME as response to paging it contains E-CGI and TAI information and also indication whether the UE is in EMM-IDLE of EMM-CONNECTED mode. If EMM-IDLE is indicated, the E-CGI can be considered as valid, because MME executed paging of the UE before answering. If EMM-CONNECTED is indicated the E-CGI may be invalid, because MME has not executed paging and it responses with the last known E-CGI of the UE. In this case MSS sends Type 0 SM over SGs to the UE, and if the received SGsAP-UPLINK-UNITDATA contains E-CGI, that is taken as valid information. If SGsAP-UPLINK-UNITDATA does not contain E-CGI, then MSS uses the last known E-CGI in further procedures.When the MSS has a valid E-CGI it maps this to a 2G/3G CGI and sends that in MAP PSI response. The counter is updated if Type 0 SM delivery on SGs interface was successful. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: MTRF_ATI_ATT
kpi_info.use: When the MSC or VLR address of the new MSS is not available and it is asked by MAP AnyTimeInterrogation operation. The counter is updated only for pre-paging. The counter shows the success and failed events as attempt. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.use: When the MSC or VLR address of the new MSS is not available and it is asked by MAP AnyTimeInterrogation operation and the answer to the query is success. The counter is updated only for pre-paging. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: MTRF_SRI_FOR_LCS_ATT
kpi_info.use: When the MSC or VLR address of the new MSS is not available and it is asked by MAP SendRoutingInfoForLCS operation. The counter shows the success and failed events as attempt. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: MTRF_SRI_FOR_LCS_SUCC
kpi_info.use: When the MSC or VLR address of the new MSS is not available and it is asked by MAP SendRoutingInfoForLCS operation and the answer to the query is success. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PAGING_TIMER_EXP_DUR_SGS_LAU
kpi_info.use: Number of unsuccessful MT events due to paging timer expiration during SGsAP LAU procedure. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PRN_PRESEARCH_SGS_ATTEMPT
kpi_info.use: The VLR performs search procedure on both A and Iu interfaces, as well as paging procedure on SGs interface and the reason of the paging is PRN pre-paging. The paging resources are not deleted until a mobile terminated call (MTC) is received for the subscriber (or internal timer expires). The counter is updated independently from the result of the search operation. In case of SGs paging busy means that the user has rejected the call. This means that the paging message was sent out on the SGs interface and a negative response was received. This is different from the 2G/3G busy case where the paging message is NOT sent out on the A/Iu interface. In case of SGs interface the busy cases also should be counted as paging/searching attempts. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PRN_PRESEARCH_SGS_SUCCESS
kpi_info.use: The VLR performs search procedure on both A and Iu interface, as well as paging procedure on SGs interface and the paging result is successful and the reason of the paging is PRN pre-paging. The paging resources are not deleted until a mobile terminated call (MTC) is received for the subscriber (or internal timer expires). The counter is updated when both the search/paging procedure and the fallback to the CS domain by the UE have been performed successfully. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PRN_PRESEARCH_SGS_ATT_SUCC
kpi_info.use: The number of search attempts on A and Iu interface, as well as the number of paging requests sent on SGs interface when the searching/paging result is successful and the reason of the paging is PRN pre-paging. The paging resources are not deleted until a mobile terminated call (MTC) is received for the subscriber (or internal timer expires). Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PRN_PRESEARCH_SGS_ATT_FAIL
kpi_info.use: The number of search attempts on A and Iu interface, as well as the number of paging requests sent on SGs interface when the searching/paging result is failed and the reason of the paging is PRN pre-paging. In case of SGs paging busy means that the user has rejected the call. This means that the paging message was sent out on the SGs interface and a negative response was received. This is different from the 2G/3G busy case where the paging message is NOT sent out on the A/Iu interface. In case of SGs interface the busy cases also should be counted as paging/searching fails. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PRN_PREPAGING_SGS_ATTEMPT
kpi_info.use: The VLR performs paging procedure on SGs interface and the reason of the paging is PRN pre-paging. The paging resources are not deleted until a mobile terminated call (MTC) is received for the subscriber (or internal timer expires). The counter is updated independently from the result of the search operation. In case of SGs paging busy means that the user has rejected the call. This means that the paging message was sent out on the SGs interface and a negative response was received. This is different from the 2G/3G busy case where the paging message is NOT sent out on the A/Iu interface. In case of SGs interface the busy cases also should be counted as paging/searching attempts. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PRN_PREPAGING_SGS_SUCCESS
kpi_info.use: The VLR performs paging procedure on SGs interface and the paging result is successful and the reason of the paging is PRN pre-paging. The paging resources are not deleted until a mobile terminated call (MTC) is received for the subscriber (or internal timer expires). The counter is updated when both the paging procedure and the fallback to the CS domain by the UE have been performed successfully. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: PRN_PREPAGING_SGS_FB_DIFF_MSS
kpi_info.use: The VLR performs paging procedure on SGs interface and the reason of the paging is PRN pre-paging but the UE make CS fallback to a different MSS. The counter is updated when VLR receives Cancel Location from HLR or Send Identification from another MSC/VLR, so UE have made successful Location Update to another MSC during CS fallback. Measured object: VLR

kpi_info.title: MTRF_PRN_RELAY_ATT
kpi_info.use: The measured object is VLR. The Map Provide Roaming Number is relayed to the new VMSS due to MT re-routing. This counter is updated if pre-paging has happened, and the result of PRN relay is success, or failed. The counter shows the success and failed events as attempt.

kpi_info.title: MTRF_PRN_RELAY_SUCC
kpi_info.use: The measured object is VLR. The Map Provide Roaming Number is relayed to the new VMSS due to MT re-routing. This counter is updated if pre-paging has happened, and the result of PRN relay is success.
